<subSubSection id="C3276FE1FFFDF52C0F6BDE60FB29FD76" pageId="16" pageNumber="523" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B823C6AFFFDF52C0F6BDE60FC1CFD88" blockId="16.[810,1420,529,727]" box="[810,930,529,553]" pageId="16" pageNumber="523">
<figureCitation id="130620EFFFFDF52C0F6BDE60FC1CFD88" box="[810,930,529,553]" captionStart="Figure 17" captionStartId="31.[168,231,1853,1873]" captionTargetBox="[168,1419,160,1829]" captionTargetId="figure-37@31.[168,1419,160,1829]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="Figure 17. OROBANCHACEAE A. Esterhazya splendida. POACEAE B. Andropogon bicornis. C. A. lateralis. D. A. leucostachyus. E. Anthaenantia lanata. F. Aristida jubata. G. Arthropogon villosus." pageId="16" pageNumber="523">Figure 17G</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B823C6AFFFDF52C0F6BDE49FB29FD76" blockId="16.[810,1420,529,727]" pageId="16" pageNumber="523">
<emphasis id="B949E078FFFDF52C0F6BDE49FC72FDF1" bold="true" box="[810,972,568,592]" pageId="16" pageNumber="523">Identification.</emphasis>
Perennial tussock grass, 
<quantity id="4CC5918FFFFDF52C0953DE49FA35FDF1" box="[1298,1419,568,592]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="523" unit="cm" value="65.0" valueMax="90.0" valueMin="40.0">40–90 cm</quantity>
height. Leaf–blades linear, glabrous or hirsute, 
<quantity id="4CC5918FFFFDF52C0908DE2BFCF5FD32" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.2" pageId="16" pageNumber="523" unit="cm" value="16.0" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="12.0">12–20 cm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity id="4CC5918FFFFDF52C0FCEDE0DFBB7FD32" box="[911,1033,636,660]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="523" unit="cm" value="0.7" valueMax="0.8" valueMin="0.6">0.6–0.8 cm</quantity>
wide, ligulate. Distinguished by its open panicle, 
<quantity id="4CC5918FFFFDF52C0F86DEECFB9BFD14" box="[967,1061,669,693]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="7.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="523" unit="cm" value="8.5" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="7.0">7–10 cm</quantity>
long, containing hairy spikelets with apical awn 3.5–5.0 mm long.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3276FE1FFFDF52C0F6BDE9AFBC8FC34" pageId="16" pageNumber="523" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B823C6AFFFDF52C0F6BDE9AFAFDFC84" blockId="16.[810,1419,747,805]" pageId="16" pageNumber="523">
<emphasis id="B949E078FFFDF52C0F6BDE9AFC27FCA2" bold="true" box="[810,921,747,771]" pageId="16" pageNumber="523">Remarks.</emphasis>
An unusual species on the native grassland, occurring mainly over the shallow and rocky soil.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B823C6AFFFDF52C0F6BDF48FBC8FC34" blockId="16.[810,1420,825,1057]" pageId="16" pageNumber="523">
<emphasis id="B949E078FFFDF52C0F6BDF48FC56FCF3" bold="true" box="[810,1000,825,850]" pageId="16" pageNumber="523">Brazilian range.</emphasis>
Midwest, North (PA state), Northeast (BA and CE states), South (
<collectingRegion id="49F9F288FFFDF52C0819DF2AFB0AFCD2" box="[1112,1204,859,883]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="16" pageNumber="523">PR state</collectingRegion>
) and Southeast (except ES and RJ states) regions.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
